# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: captain-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The **2023 Major League Baseball season** (MLB) began on March 30, while the regular season ended on October 1.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The World Series then began on October 27 and ended on November 1 with the Texas Rangers defeating the Arizona Diamondbacks in five games to win their first title in franchise history.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The 93rd All-Star Game was played on July 11, hosted by the Seattle Mariners at T-Mobile Park in Seattle, Washington, with the National League winning, 3–2.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This season saw the introduction of several rule changes: in an effort to create a quicker pace of play, a pitch clock was introduced along with other minor changes, while limits on defensive shifts and larger bases were also introduced.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On August 24, 2022, Major League Baseball released its 2023 schedule.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] There were 162 games scheduled for all teams.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This season was the first MLB season of a new balanced schedule in which every team played each other at least once, similar to the NBA and NHL.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The new balanced schedule included 13 games against their division rivals, totaling 52 games.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Each team played six games against six opponents and seven games against four opponents in the same league for a total of 64 games.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Each team also played 46 interleague games, including a four-game home-and-home series against their designated interleague rival.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] As part of the "MLB World Tour", the San Francisco Giants and the San Diego Padres played a two-game series at Alfredo Harp Helú Stadium in Mexico City on April 29–30, while the St.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Louis Cardinals and the Chicago Cubs played a two-game series at London Stadium in London on June 24–25.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The 93rd All-Star Game was played on July 11, hosted by the Seattle Mariners at T-Mobile Park in Seattle.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The MLB Little League Classic featured the Philadelphia Phillies against the Washington Nationals on August 20.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Opening Day, March 30, featured all thirty teams, the first time since 1968 that every team has started their season on the same day.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The MLB at Field of Dreams game was not held in 2023 due to the construction of a new youth baseball and softball complex at the Field of Dreams site near Dyersville, Iowa.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On September 8, 2022, MLB announced a set of rules changes that would take effect in 2023.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Spring training for the 2023 season began in late February and lasted through March.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Teams began workouts and practice for spring training beginning in late February.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Pitchers and catchers reported first, followed by position players a few days later.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Prior to the start of the regular season, each team played between 27 and 33 spring training games, beginning on February 24.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] There were several times during spring training when a team had two different squads playing different teams simultaneously.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] In addition to spring training games, teams occasionally played exhibition games with non-MLB teams, such as Minor League Baseball teams, independent teams, or college teams.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] These exhibition games were not counted in the spring training standings.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Spring training ended on March 28, two days before the Opening Day.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Postseason began on October 3 and ended with Game 5 on November 1.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Players are selected through fan votes (50%) and votes from a panel of experts (50%).
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The winners are selected based on merit, with no set number of nominees per position and no distinction between leagues.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Six additional teams unveiled new City Connect uniforms during the season.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Starting with this season, teams may add advertisement patches to their uniforms.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Padres wore 1948 Pacific Coast League (PCL) throwbacks on April 17 in honor of Johnny Ritchey, who integrated the PCL.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Pirates wore Homestead Grays throwbacks on August 13 in the second game of a doubleheader.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Giants wore San Francisco Sea Lions throwbacks on August 26.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Astros and the Royals wore Negro Leagues throwbacks on September 16.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Astros wore uniforms of the 1950 Houston Eagles, and the Royals wore Kansas City Monarchs uniforms.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] All teams and umpires wore #42 on April 15, the 76th anniversary of Jackie Robinson's debut in the majors.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] For the second consecutive year, all teams wore the #42 in Dodger Blue font.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Players who normally wear their number on the front did not have them.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] During the postseason, the ESPN networks (including ABC) broadcast all four Wild Card Series, with Spanish-language simulcasts on ESPN Deportes.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS broadcast the National League Division Series and the National League Championship Series; TBS' postseason games were also made available on the streaming service Max's new Bleacher Report Sports Add-on tier which launched on October 5, and Spanish-language coverage was simulcast on MLB Network.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox Sports broadcast the American League Division Series, the American League Championship Series, and the World Series, with games shown on Fox and FS1, with Spanish-language simulcasts on Fox Deportes.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On February 24, 2023, the AT&T SportsNet regional sports networks sent a letter to the Rockies, Astros, and Pirates saying they had until March 31, to reach an agreement to take their local television rights back.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Discovery (WBD), the owner of the networks, intends to leave the regional sports networks business.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] If a deal is not reached the networks will file for Chapter 7 bankruptcy.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Root Sports Northwest is not affected because the Mariners already own majority control of that network.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Discovery and Major League Baseball quietly negotiated a deal to keep the remaining RSNs operational through the end of the season.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In August 2023, Boston Red Sox owner Fenway Sports Group announced its acquisition of AT&T SportsNet Pittsburgh from WBD via the co-owned Pittsburgh Penguins of the NHL, which subsequently re-launched as the NESN-operated SportsNet Pittsburgh in October.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] During the offseason, the Pittsburgh Pirates announced they would jointly own the network beginning on January 1, 2024.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In September 2023, the Houston Astros and Houston Rockets jointly acquired WBD's stake in AT&T SportsNet Southwest.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Both of those networks rebranded themselves to SportsNet Pittsburgh and the Space City Home Network, respectively, near the end of the regular season.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] However, with AT&T SportsNet Rocky Mountain failing to find new owners (either with the Colorado Rockies or some other professional sports team(s) in the area), SportsNet Rocky Mountain shut down services by October 21, 2023.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On February 15, 2023, Diamond Sports Group, owners of the Bally Sports regional sports networks, failed to make a $140 million interest payment and entered a 30-day grace period.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On March 14, Diamond Sports officially filed for Chapter 11 Bankruptcy.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Diamond had missed payments to the Diamondbacks, Rangers, Guardians, and Twins.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Diamond also entered grace periods for their payments to the Padres and Reds, which they eventually made.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On April 5, Major League Baseball filed an emergency motion asking the bankruptcy judge to order Diamond to pay the teams they missed payments to or give the media rights back to MLB.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Diamond argued that due to the impact of cord-cutting, the contract rate for the media rights of the teams was too high.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] A hearing on the matter was set for May 31.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As an interim, on April 19, the bankruptcy judge ordered Diamond Sports to pay 50% of what the Diamondbacks, Guardians, Twins, and Rangers are owed.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On June 1, after a two-day long hearing, the bankruptcy judge ordered Diamond to pay the teams fully within five days.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On May 31, Diamond officially missed a second payment to the Padres, and the Padres' television rights were returned to Major League Baseball.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Because Bally Sports San Diego, which aired Padres games, is a joint venture between the Padres and Diamond it is technically not in bankruptcy.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Therefore, this missed payment did not have the same bankruptcy protections that Diamond's other missed payments had.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The department had already worked with MLB Network staff to prepare for the possibility that it would have to take over a team's regional broadcasts on short notice, including preparing team-specific graphics packages and other elements in advance.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Chambers' team was on standby in Miami for the Padres' series against the Marlins, focusing in particular on contingencies for the May 31 game based on the deadline, and having only 24 hours' notice of the missed payment on May 30.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The MLB-produced telecasts inherited the Padres' existing broadcast team and other team-contracted staff.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Once the team returned to San Diego, MLB Local Media inherited the mobile production units and freelance employees that had been used by Bally.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On June 22, Diamond Sports Group announced its intention to reject its contract with the Diamondbacks on June 30.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Diamond and the Arizona Diamondbacks later released a joint statement pushing back the hearing to July 17 and agreeing to continue Bally Sports Arizona's broadcasts of Diamondbacks' games.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On July 18, Diamond Sports officially rejected its contract with the Diamondbacks; MLB Local Media subsequently took over production of the team's telecasts in a similar arrangement to the Padres.
[src:captain-baseball/2023-major-league-baseball-season-p02] After losing the rights earlier in the year to the Phoenix Suns and later in the year to the Arizona Coyotes to Gray Television and Scripps Sports respectively, Bally Sports Arizona began to wind down operations in October 2023, shutting down for good on October 21 that same year.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge played college baseball for the Fresno State Bulldogs, and was selected by the Yankees with the 32nd pick in the first round of the 2013 MLB draft.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After making his MLB debut in 2016, Judge won AL Rookie of the Year in 2017 by unanimous vote and finished second in AL MVP voting.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit an AL-leading 52 home runs, temporarily setting a new MLB rookie record, and became the first rookie to win the Home Run Derby.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2022, Judge won his first MVP after setting the AL single-season home run record, breaking the 61-year-old mark held by Roger Maris.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following the 2022 season, Judge re-signed with the Yankees on a nine-year, $360-million contract and was named the team's captain.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2024, he won his second MVP by unanimous vote, leading MLB in home runs and OPS while becoming the fastest MLB player to reach 300 career home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] That postseason, the Yankees won their first AL pennant in 15 years, but lost in the World Series.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He won his third MVP and second consecutive in 2025, and also captured his first batting title.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge captained United States national team during the 2026 World Baseball Classic.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was born on April 26, 1992, in Sacramento, California.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was adopted one day later by Patty and Wayne Judge, who both worked as teachers in nearby Linden.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He has an older brother, John, who was also adopted.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Growing up, Judge was a San Francisco Giants fan.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He attended Linden High School, where he was a three-sport star.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge played as a pitcher and first baseman for the baseball team, a wide receiver for the football team, and as a center for the basketball team.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As a sophomore, Judge earned All-Mother Lode League honors in varsity baseball as a first baseman.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The following year, he was named the Mother Lode League's Most Outstanding Player in basketball after leading Linden to its first league title since 1986.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As a senior, he was selected as Linden High School's Athlete of the Year and received team and Mother Lode League MVP honors in all three sports, while also being named to *The Record's* All-Area first team for each.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge set school records for single-season receiving yards (969) and touchdown receptions (17), and led the basketball team in scoring at 18.2 points per game while shooting 56% from the field and averaging 12.8 rebounds and 2.3 blocks, earning Cal-Hi Sports Division IV all-state recognition.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge graduated from Linden High in 2010.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was the sole inductee into the Linden Athletic Hall of Fame in 2019.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Several colleges recruited Judge to play tight end in football, including Notre Dame, Stanford, and UCLA, but he preferred baseball.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Oakland Athletics selected him in the 31st round of the 2010 MLB draft.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He opted to enroll at California State University, Fresno, to play for the Bulldogs baseball team.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2011, Fresno State shared the Western Athletic Conference (WAC) regular season title, won the WAC Tournament, and qualified for the NCAA Division I baseball tournament.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the WAC Freshman of the Year, earned All-WAC First Team and All-Tournament Team honors, and was selected as a Freshman All-American by Louisville Slugger.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2012, Fresno State repeated as WAC tournament champions, with Judge earning All-WAC First Team honors for the second consecutive year and another selection to the All-Tournament Team.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished the season tied for second in the conference with 13 stolen bases and ranked fifth with 47 runs scored.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also won the 2012 College Home Run Derby.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] That summer, he played collegiate summer baseball for the Brewster Whitecaps of the Cape Cod Baseball League, where he received the team's Citizenship Award for being a positive team member.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As a junior in 2013, Judge led the Bulldogs in home runs (12), doubles (15), and runs batted in (36), earning All-Mountain West Conference First Team honors.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was named to the all-conference team in all three of his seasons for the Bulldogs—in the WAC in his first two seasons, and the Mountain West as a junior.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] (The Bulldogs joined the Mountain West in July 2012, before his junior season).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was honored with a jersey retirement celebration at halftime of a Fresno State football game on November 18, 2023.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The following day, the Fresno State baseball team formally retired his #29 jersey.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees drafted Judge in the first round of the 2013 MLB draft with the 32nd overall selection, a pick the team received as compensation after losing Nick Swisher in free agency.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge signed with the Yankees and received a $1.8 million signing bonus.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He tore a quadriceps femoris muscle while participating in a base running drill, which kept him out of the 2013 season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge made his professional debut with the Charleston RiverDogs of the Class A South Atlantic League in 2014.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had a .333 batting average (6th in the league), .428 on-base percentage (OBP; 3rd), .530 slugging percentage (SLG; 6th), a .958 on-base plus slugging (OPS) and hit nine home runs with 45 RBIs in 65 games for Charleston.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees promoted him to the Tampa Yankees of the Class A-Advanced Florida State League in June, where he hit .283 with a .411 OBP (2nd in the league), .442 SLG, eight home runs, and 33 RBIs in 66 games for Tampa.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the season, he played for the Scottsdale Scorpions in the Arizona Fall League, batting .278 with four home runs in 24 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees invited Judge to spring training as a non-roster player in 2015.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He began the season with the Trenton Thunder of the Double-A Eastern League.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After posting a .284/.350/.510 slash line with 12 home runs (tied for 9th in the league) in 63 games for Trenton, the Yankees promoted Judge to the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre RailRiders of the Triple-A International League in June.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was chosen to play in the 2015 All-Star Futures Game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees did not include Judge in their September call-ups.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge batted .224/.308/.373 with eight home runs in 61 games for Scranton/Wilkes-Barre.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees invited Judge to spring training in 2016, and he returned to Triple-A to began the season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named to the International League All-Star Team in 2016 but did not play in the All-Star Game after he spent a month on the disabled list due to a knee sprain.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 93 games for the RailRiders, Judge batted .270/.366/.489 with 19 home runs (4th in the league), 62 runs (tied for 8th), and 65 RBIs (tied for 7th).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge made his MLB debut on August 13, 2016, starting in right field against the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In his first MLB at-bat, Judge hit a home run off Matt Andriese; the previous batter, Tyler Austin, also making his MLB debut, had done the same.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This marked the first time that two teammates had hit home runs in their first MLB career at-bats in the same game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also hit a home run in his second MLB game, becoming the second Yankees player, after Joe Lefebvre in 1980, to homer in each of his first two MLB games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In his debut season, Judge played in 27 games and batted .179/.263/.345 with 15 hits, four home runs, two doubles and 10 runs batted in and he struck out 42 times in 95 plate appearances.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His season ended prematurely when he was placed on the 15-day disabled list with a grade two right oblique strain on September 13, 2016.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees named Judge their Opening Day right fielder against the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had his first multi-home run game on April 28 against the Baltimore Orioles to help the Yankees win 14–11, coming back from a 9–1 deficit.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] One of the home runs had a measured exit velocity of 119.4 miles per hour (192.2 km/h), the fastest exit velocity for a home run measured by Statcast since it was adopted in 2015.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] (This record would later be broken by teammate Giancarlo Stanton on August 9, 2018, when Stanton launched a home run with an exit velocity of 121.7 miles per hour (195.9 km/h).) Judge ended April with 10 home runs, tying the rookie record set by José Abreu and Trevor Story.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was named the American League's (AL) Rookie of the Month for April.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In April, he had a .303 batting average, 10 home runs, 20 RBIs, and a .411 OBP in 22 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees debuted a cheering section in the right-field seats of Yankee Stadium on May 22.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Called "The Judge's Chambers", the section spans three rows in section 104 and contains 18 seats.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Fans were chosen by the team to sit there and are outfitted with black robes, wigs, and foam gavels.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In a game against the Oakland Athletics on May 28, Judge hit his first career grand slam.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named AL Rookie of the Month once again for May.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In May, he had a .347 batting average, seven home runs, 17 RBIs, and a .441 OBP in 26 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 10, Judge hit a home run that had an exit velocity of 121.1 miles per hour (194.9 km/h), again setting a new record for the hardest measured by Statcast.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The following day, Judge went 4-for-4 with two home runs; one of the home runs traveled 496 feet (151 m), the longest home run hit that season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 12, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His week ended with him leading the AL in all three Triple Crown categories.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the AL Player of the Month for June, batting .337 with 10 home runs, 25 RBIs and a .481 OBP.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His performance in June also earned him his third consecutive AL Rookie of the Month award, the longest streak since Mike Trout won four in a row in 2012.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge had a 32-game on-base streak, including reaching base in every game in June.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 2, Judge was voted as a starting outfielder to the MLB All-Star Game, receiving 4,488,702 votes, the most of any player in the AL.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge broke Joe DiMaggio's record for most home runs hit by a Yankees rookie with his 30th on July 7.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second rookie to hit 30 home runs before the All-Star break, following Mark McGwire in 1987, and the first Yankee to do so since Alex Rodriguez in 2007.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Before the All-Star break, Judge hit .329 with 30 home runs and 66 RBIs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the Home Run Derby, besting Minnesota Twins third baseman Miguel Sanó 11–10 in the final round to become the first rookie to win the Derby outright.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After his performance, MLB commissioner Rob Manfred stated that Judge is a player "who can become the face of the game".
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 21, Judge hit a home run that almost travelled out of Safeco Field.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The ball was hit so hard that Statcast initially did not measure the details of the home run.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 16, Judge hit a 457-foot (139 m) home run at Citi Field that reached the third deck.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also broke a record for position players by striking out in a 33rd consecutive game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 20, Judge tied pitcher Bill Stoneman's streak of striking out in 37 consecutive games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 4, Judge became the first AL rookie with 100 walks in a season since Al Rosen in 1950, and the first MLB rookie to do so since Jim Gilliam in 1953.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 10, Judge walked for the 107th time, the most walks by a rookie in a season since Ted Williams in 1939.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the same game, he also became the second rookie in MLB history to hit 40 home runs in a season since McGwire (1987).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He joined Babe Ruth (1920), Lou Gehrig (1927), Joe DiMaggio (1937) and Mickey Mantle (1956) as the only Yankees to hit 40 home runs in a season at age 25 or younger.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 25, Judge hit his 49th and 50th home runs, tying and surpassing Mark McGwire's single-season rookie home run record.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 30, Judge hit his 52nd home run of the season and his 33rd at Yankee Stadium, surpassing Babe Ruth's single-season record (set in 1921) for most home runs hit by a Yankees player at his home ballpark.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the conclusion of September, Judge won AL Player of the Month for the second time and Rookie of the Month for the fourth time.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge appeared in 155 games and finished the regular season slashing .284/.422/.627 with 154 hits, 52 home runs, three triples, 24 doubles, 114 RBI, 127 walks, 11 intentional walks and nine stolen bases.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He led the AL in home runs, runs scored (128), and walks (a major-league rookie record 127).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also struck out an MLB-leading 208 times, breaking the Yankees record previously set by Curtis Granderson in 2012 and a rookie record previously set by Kris Bryant in 2015.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] With the Yankees finishing the year with a 91–71 record, the team clinched a Wild Card in the postseason.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the Wild Card Game against the Minnesota Twins, Judge hit a home run en route to an 8–4 Yankees victory.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In Game 3 of the AL Division Series (ALDS), Judge robbed Francisco Lindor of a home run, preserving the tie game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge struck out 16 times in the series, setting an ALDS record.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the Yankees defeated the Cleveland Indians in the ALDS, Judge hit three home runs for the Yankees in the AL Championship Series (ALCS).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also robbed Yulieski Gurriel of a potential home run in the Yankees' Game 7 ALCS loss to the Houston Astros.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished with 27 strikeouts in the postseason, a major league record at the time.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] End-of-season awards for Judge included selection as an outfielder on *Baseball America*'s All-MLB Team, the Players Choice Award for Outstanding AL Rookie, and a Silver Slugger Award.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was unanimously voted as the AL Rookie of the Year.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He went on to finish second in the voting for the AL Most Valuable Player Award to Jose Altuve, receiving two out of 30 first place votes.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On November 21, it was revealed that Judge had undergone arthroscopic surgery in his left shoulder for a cartilage cleanup, an injury dating back to April of that year.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On March 31, Judge made his first career start at center field in the majors.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At 6 feet 7 inches (2.01 m) tall and weighing 282 pounds (128 kg), he became the tallest and heaviest player in baseball history to play the position.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Batting .277 with 25 home runs and 58 RBIs, Judge was named a starting outfielder for the All-Star Game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge hit a solo home run off National League starter Max Scherzer.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 26, a 93 mph fastball by Kansas City Royals pitcher Jakob Junis hit Judge on his right wrist and he left the game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Later, an MRI/CT scan revealed that he suffered a fractured ulnar styloid bone in his wrist.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] No surgery was required, and initial reports gave a three-week timetable for Judge to recover.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The injury took longer to heal than expected, with Judge missing close to two months.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 18, Judge returned to the starting lineup.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished the season with a .278 batting average, 27 home runs, and 67 RBIs in 112 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees beat the Oakland Athletics in the Wild Card Game but were defeated, three games to one, by the Red Sox in the ALDS.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge started the season off with a .288 batting average, five home runs, and 11 RBIs in his first 20 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] However, on April 20, Judge suffered a left oblique strain while hitting a single in the sixth inning against the Kansas City Royals.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 27, Judge hit his 17th home run of the season and 100th home run of his career.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Coming in his 371st game, it made him the third-fastest MLB player to hit 100 home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge hit a home run over Fenway Park's Green Monster for the first time on September 8.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] With this home run, the 2019 Yankees set a new franchise record for team home runs in a season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2019, Judge batted .272/.381/.540, with 103 hits, 27 home runs, one triple,18 doubles and 55 RBIs in 447 plate appearances across 102 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had the fastest average exit velocity on balls hit in play among major leaguers at 95.9 mph (154.3 km/h).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He led the league in defensive runs saved as a right fielder (19 runs saved, tied with Cody Bellinger) but did so in fewer innings (775+1⁄3 compared to 911+1⁄3 for Bellinger).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge earned the Wilson Defensive Player of the Year Award for his position in right field.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During spring training in March, Judge felt soreness in his pectoral area.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] It was revealed that he had suffered a stress fracture in his ribs and was shut down for at least two weeks.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] However, the start of the season was delayed until July.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge began the shortened 2020 season with five consecutive games with a home run (6 during the span), launching a 419-feet, 108 mph three-run shot off of Boston Red Sox pitcher Matt Hall.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His streak ended on August 3 when he went 2-for-4 without a home run.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] It was the longest home run streak by a Yankees player since Alex Rodriguez (September 4–9, 2007).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 14, Judge was placed on the 10-day injured list with a right calf strain.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 26, he was again placed on the 10-day injured list after straining the same calf the day he returned against the Atlanta Braves.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He finished the season slashing .257/.336/.554 with 26 hits, nine home runs, three doubles and 22 RBIs over 28 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the playoffs, he batted 4-for-30 with 3 home runs and 5 RBI as the Yankees lost to Tampa Bay in the ALDS.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the week of May 10–16, Judge earned his fourth career AL Player of the Week Award.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge had a slash line of .571/.640/1.333 with eight runs scored, 12 hits, a double, five home runs, six RBIs, and three walks in six games (five multi-hit games and his 13th career multi-homer game).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also hit his 130th career home run, the second-most in MLB history through 460 career games, trailing only Ryan Howard (142).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On May 23, Judge recorded his first career walk-off RBI, taking a walk on a 3–1 pitch from Liam Hendriks of the Chicago White Sox.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 9, Judge recorded his 500th career hit during a game against the Houston Astros by hitting a double to left field off pitcher Brandon Bielak.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second-fastest Yankee to 500 hits and 100 home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He accomplished the feat in his 506th game, with only Joe DiMaggio getting there faster, at 395 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the starting right fielder in the All-Star Game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following the All-Star Game, Judge was placed on the COVID-19 injured list after testing positive for the virus.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge returned against the Tampa Bay Rays on July 27.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 12, in the Field of Dreams game in Iowa, Judge hit two multiple-run home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also hit two home runs on September 11 against the New York Mets with his 31st and 32nd home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On October 3, the last game of the regular season, Judge recorded his first career walk-off hit, a single that scored Tyler Wade to beat Tampa Bay 1–0 and clinch a Wild Card spot for the Yankees.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the Wild Card Game, Judge became the first Yankee to be ruled out at home plate on a hit in a winner-take-all game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge finished the 2021 season batting .287/.373/.544 with 158 hits, 39 home runs, 24 doubles, 98 RBI, 75 walks, two intentional walks, and six stolen bases.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the season, Judge won a Fielding Bible Award for his defensive excellence and his second Silver Slugger Award.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On November 23, Judge was named to the First Team of the All-MLB Team as an outfielder.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Before the 2022 Yankees season, Judge and the Yankees were unsuccessful in negotiating a long-term contract.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] General manager Brian Cashman told ESPN that the team offered Judge $17 million in arbitration and a seven-year extension worth $213.5 million.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge avoided salary arbitration and signed a one-year, $19 million contract on June 24, with additional $250,000 bonuses for winning each of the MVP Award and the World Series MVP Award.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge slashed .293/.361/.600 with six home runs in April.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit his first career walk-off home run on May 10 off Toronto Blue Jays closer Jordan Romano.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the AL Player of the Month Award for May.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the month, Judge slashed .311/.378/.699 with 12 home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit his second walk-off home run on June 26 against the Houston Astros.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was elected as a starter for the All-Star Game, receiving the most fan votes of any player in the AL.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This was his second consecutive and fourth overall All-Star selection.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge slugged his third walk-off homer for the season against the visiting Kansas City Royals on July 28, tying Mickey Mantle for most by a Yankee in a season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won back-to-back AL Player of the Week Awards for the weeks ending July 24 and 31.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also claimed the AL Player of the Month Award for July after batting .333/.436/.806 with 13 home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 30, Judge became the second-fastest player in MLB history to hit 200 home runs (behind Ryan Howard), launching a two-run shot off of Jon Heasley of the Kansas City Royals.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 29, during a game against the Los Angeles Angels, Judge hit his 50th home run for the season, coming off reliever Ryan Tepera.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became only the tenth player in MLB history and third player in Yankees franchise history to record multiple 50 home run seasons.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge hit his 55th home run during the first game of a doubleheader against the Minnesota Twins on September 7 off rookie starting pitcher Louie Varland.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the fourth player in MLB history to hit at least 55 home runs and steal at least 15 bases in a season, joining Babe Ruth (1921), Sammy Sosa (1998), and Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's 60th home run came on September 20.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 28, Judge hit his 61st home run off Tim Mayza of the Toronto Blue Jays, tying Roger Maris for the most home runs in a single season in AL history.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the second game of a doubleheader (and the Yankees' second-to-last regular season game) against the Texas Rangers at Globe Life Field on October 4, Judge hit his 62nd home run off Jesús Tinoco, setting the new single-season AL home run record.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was selected as the AL Player of the Week for the week of September 29–October 5.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He claimed his third AL Player of the Month Award of the season in September.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2022, Judge led the major leagues with 62 home runs, 133 runs scored, 131 RBI (tied with Pete Alonso of the Mets), 111 walks, and batted .311/.425/.686 with 177 hits, 28 doubles, and 19 intentional walks, while stealing 16 bases in 19 attempts, in 157 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was denied the AL triple crown, as Luis Arráez of the Minnesota Twins had a batting average that was five points higher than Judge's.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the AL MVP Award, earning 28 of 30 first-place votes.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's 2022 campaign is considered one of the best offensive seasons in major league history.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On December 30, he was voted the Associated Press (AP) "Male Athlete of the Year" by a panel of 40 sports writers and editors from news outlets throughout the United States.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge just edged out Los Angeles Angels two-way star and 2021's winner Shohei Ohtani in voting.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was also selected as the Time Magazine Athlete of the Year.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees qualified for the postseason, facing the Cleveland Guardians in the ALDS, where Judge slashed .200/.238/.500 with two home runs, as the Yankees defeated the Guardians in five games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the ALCS, Judge hit just .063/.118/.063 with one hit and a walk as the Yankees were swept in four games by the Houston Astros, who would go on to win the World Series.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the 2022 season, Judge became a free agent.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees extended the qualifying offer of a one-year contract worth $19.65 million to Judge, but he declined.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During free agency, he was pursued by the San Diego Padres and San Francisco Giants as well as the Yankees.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By early December 2022, the Padres offered Judge over $400 million, according to Judge's agent.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees were only offering $320 million over eight years.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] A new deal with the Yankees was created in a phone call between Judge and Yankees owner Hal Steinbrenner, when Steinbrenner offered to add a ninth year and an additional $40 million.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] That became the foundation of an agreement that the Yankees, and Judge signed on December 20, 2022, with the nine-year, $360 million deal breaking the record for the largest free agent deal in MLB history.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In a press conference on the following day, Steinbrenner named Judge the 16th captain of the Yankees and the first since Derek Jeter had retired eight years earlier.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On 2023 MLB Opening Day at Yankee Stadium, Judge hit his first home run of the year off San Francisco Giants ace Logan Webb into Monument Park.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge went on the 10-day injured list after a mild hip strain suffered while sliding into base playing against the Minnesota Twins at Target Field on April 26.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge returned against the Oakland Athletics on May 9.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge received the AL Player of the Week Award for the week of May 15–21.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Despite missing the first week of games in May, Judge also won the AL Player of the Month Award for May after batting .342/.474/.882 with 12 home runs in 21 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 3, Judge crashed through a closed gate in the outfield wall at Dodger Stadium while recording a fly out off JD Martinez, causing a sprain to his toe and leading to him missing 42 games, with the Yankees going 19–23 in his absence.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Despite the injury, Judge was elected to the All Star Game but was unable to participate, and he was replaced in the lineup by the Texas Rangers' Adolis Garcia.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge returned against the Baltimore Orioles at Camden Yards on July 28.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 23, Judge hit three home runs, including a grand slam, against the Washington Nationals at Yankee Stadium.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He repeated the feat at home against the Arizona Diamondbacks less than a month later on September 22, becoming the first Yankee to homer three times in a game twice in a season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won his second AL Player of the Week Award of the season on September 24.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 2, Judge hit his 250th career home run (30th of the season) off of Astros ace Justin Verlander in the fifth inning.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] It was his 810th career game, setting a new record as the fastest player to reach 250 home runs in MLB history, passing marks previously set by Ryan Howard (855 games) and Ralph Kiner (871 games).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Despite missing 56 games, Judge hit 37 home runs in 2023, putting him on a 55 home run pace had he played a full season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He slashed .267/.406/.613, from 106 games, his second consecutive year with an OPS over 1.000 and his third overall.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He had 98 hits, 16 doubles, 75 RBI, 88 walks, 9 intentional walks, and 3 stolen bases (caught stealing once).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees finished the regular season in fourth place in the AL East and missed the playoffs for the first time since 2016.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge received the Roberto Clemente Award before Game 3 of the World Series.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The award acknowledged his exemplary character and charity work promoting responsible youth and civic citizenship in New York and California through his ALL RISE Foundation.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was also selected to the All-MLB Team for the third successive year, this time to the second team.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] As captain, Judge appeared to take a more hands-on approach towards the Yankees organization, having conversations with Steinbrenner about the team direction and potential changes following the Yankees missing the postseason.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following an injury-interrupted spring training, Judge started the 2024 season slowly, hitting .180 through the first three weeks of April.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge primarily played at center field early in the season but also made his first major league appearance in left field when Alex Verdugo was on paternity leave.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By late April, Judge appeared more comfortable and improved his performance at the plate, collecting eight hits and three home runs along with six walks in the final week of the month.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was selected as the AL Player of the Week for the week of May 19, after going 10-for-20 and slugging 1.200 with three home runs and five doubles in this period.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was also selected as the AL Player of the Month for May, having hit 14 home runs and 12 doubles in the month, with 27 RBI, slashing .361/.479/.918.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This marked Judge's seventh AL Player of the Month selection, and his third consecutive May honor.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also completed a homecoming of sorts, playing his first series at Oracle Park against the San Francisco Giants, where he went 6-for-10 with three home runs and six RBI as the Yankees swept the series.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By the end of May, Judge improved his season slash line to .277/.405/.643, with an OPS of 1.048.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] For the week ending June 9, Judge received his second AL Player of the Week award for 2024.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the six-game homestand split against the Minnesota Twins and Los Angeles Dodgers, Judge slashed .500/.630/1.200 with three home runs and 12 RBI.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Following a 3-for-4 game against the Dodgers on June 9, Judge raised his season batting average to over .300 for the first time.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At end of June, Judge led the majors in home runs (31), RBI (82), and OPS (1.144), and he was second in the AL in batting average (.316) among qualified hitters.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won the AL Player of the Month Award again in June, for the second consecutive month, slashing .409/.514/.864, with 11 home runs and 37 RBI for the month.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 27, Judge was announced as a starting outfielder for the AL in the All-Star Game, having received the most votes.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This was the second time in three seasons that he received the most All-Star votes.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 14, batting against Chad Kuhl of the Chicago White Sox, Judge hit his 300th career home run in the Yankees' 10–2 victory.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the fastest player to ever hit 300 home runs, taking him 955 games and 3,431 at-bats, surpassing both Ralph Kiner's record by 132 games and Babe Ruth's by 400 at-bats.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second hitter to record his 300th home run prior to his 1,000th hit.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He hit his 50th and 51st home runs of the season on August 25, becoming the fifth player in MLB history with three-plus seasons of 50 or more home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the AL Player of the Week for the week of August 19–25, following a strong homestand against the Cleveland Guardians and Colorado Rockies.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On August 26, Judge collected his 1,000th career hit, a line-drive single to right field against José Ferrer at Nationals Park.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge received the August AL Player of the Month Award, his third monthly award of the season, after slashing .389/.530/.856.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 13, Judge hit a go-ahead grand slam at Yankee Stadium against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This ended a 16-game homerless streak, the longest of his major league career.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge ended the regular season slashing .322/.458/.701, with 180 hits, 58 home runs, one triple, 36 doubles, 144 RBI, 133 walks, 20 intentional walks and 10 stolen bases from 155 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The Yankees won the ALCS against the Cleveland Guardians in five games in which Judge hit two home runs and notched five RBIs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In his first World Series, Judge went 1-for-12 with seven strikeouts in the first three games of the series as the Yankees fell into a 3–0 series deficit.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In Game 5, Judge hit his first World Series home run as the Yankees jumped out to a 5–0 lead, but a series of defensive mistakes, including Judge's first error of the year, allowed the lead to slip away as the Yankees lost the game 7–6, and thus the series in five games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After the season, Judge won the AL MVP Award.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He became the second Yankee player to win the award unanimously, following Mickey Mantle in 1956.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On March 29, Judge hit three home runs and a double with eight RBIs against the Milwaukee Brewers, his third career three-homer game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On March 31, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week for the opening week of the season after going 6-for-11 and slugging 1.818 with four home runs and 11 RBIs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 3, Judge hit his 500th career extra-base hit with a first-inning, three-run home run off the Arizona Diamondbacks' Merrill Kelly.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge became the third-fastest Yankee to reach the milestone in terms of games played, having done so in his 999th game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the same game, Judge became the first player in MLB history with five home runs and 15 RBIs in his team's first six games of the season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 4 against the Pittsburgh Pirates, playing in his 1,000th game for the Yankees, Judge registered his 321st home run, equaling Babe Ruth's record for home runs in his first 1,000 Yankees games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] By the end of April, Judge was slashing .427/.521/.761 with 10 home runs and 32 RBI.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won with the AL Player of the Month Award for April, the tenth of his career.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On May 30 against the Los Angeles Dodgers, Judge and Shohei Ohtani became the first reigning MVPs ever to each hit a home run in the first inning of the same game.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge was named the AL Player of the Month again in May, after slashing .364/.453/.798, with 11 home runs on the month.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His 11th career monthly award is the most in AL history, surpassing Alex Rodriguez.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 26, Judge was announced as a starting outfielder for the AL in the All-Star Game, having received the most votes for the third time in four seasons and the second straight year.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 12, Judge hit his 350th career home run against the Chicago Cubs; he accomplished this in 1,088 games, breaking the record of 1,280 games by Mark McGwire.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On July 27, Judge was placed on the 10-day injury list with a flexor strain in his right elbow, following discomfort while throwing from the outfield against the Toronto Blue Jays.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was reactivated on August 5, mostly appearing as designated hitter in the following month, before making more regular appearances in the outfield from mid-September.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 9 against the Detroit Tigers, Judge hit his 359th home run, passing Yogi Berra for fifth place on the Yankees all-time home run list.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 11, two more home runs against the Tigers brought his total to 361, tying Joe DiMaggio for fourth all-time in Yankees history.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The next day, he passed DiMaggio with his 362nd against the Red Sox.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This was his 19th first-inning home run of the season, breaking a tie with Alex Rodriguez (2001) and his own mark from 2024 for the most home runs by a player in a single inning in a season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 15, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week after going 9-for-20 with a 1.760 OPS, five home runs, and five RBIs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 24, he hit two home runs against the Chicago White Sox, bringing him to the 50 home run mark in a season for the fourth time, tying Babe Ruth, Mark McGwire, and Sammy Sosa for the most such seasons in MLB history.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge and Ruth are the only Yankees to have consecutive years of 50 or more homers.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On September 29, Judge was named the AL Player of the Week after going 9-for-20 with four home runs, nine RBIs and an OPS of 1.693.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He also won the AL Player of the Month for September after slashing .391/.440/.772 with 10 home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge finished the regular season with a .331 batting average, leading the major leagues, and winning his first career batting title.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At 6 feet 7 inches, he became the tallest batting champion in MLB history.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He slashed .331/.457/.688 with 53 home runs, 179 hits, two triples, 30 doubles, 114 RBI, 124 walks, 36 intentional walks, and 12 stolen bases in 152 games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His 53 home runs were the most ever by a batting champion.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's 36 intentional walks broke the AL single-season record, overtaking Ted Williams' record of 34 set in the 1957 season.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In the AL Wild Card Series against the Boston Red Sox, Judge went 4-for-11 with one walk and one RBI.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On October 7 at Yankee Stadium, with the Yankees facing being swept in the AL Division Series by the Toronto Blue Jays, Judge went 3-4 and hit the tying three-run home run off the foul pole as the Yankees came back from a 6–1 run deficit to keep the series alive.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] This effort answered some of the lingering criticism of his previously underwhelming postseason performances, which had amplified after he had struck out with the bases loaded in the series opener.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge ended the postseason slashing .500/.581/.692 with 13 hits, one home run, two doubles and seven RBI across seven games as the Yankees were eliminated by the Blue Jays in four games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge won his third career and second consecutive AL MVP award.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In a tight race, Judge received 17 first-place votes, 4 more than Cal Raleigh.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge began the 2026 MLB season by striking out four times against the San Francisco Giants on Opening Night.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 14, Judge hit two home runs against the Los Angeles Angels at Yankee Stadium.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On May 24, Judge hit his fourth career walk-off home run to defeat the Tampa Bay Rays, ending a career-high 11 game homerless streak.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On June 5, Judge was diagnosed with a stress fracture on the right side of his first rib, which was suspected to have been suffered during a game against the Houston Astros approximately six weeks previously.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He was placed on the ten-day injured list from June 2 and was expected to miss at least four weeks.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge did not compete in the 2023 World Baseball Classic (WBC), choosing instead to focus on preparing for his season with the Yankees, given his recent contract and captaincy.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On April 14, 2025, Judge was named captain of Team USA ahead of the 2026 WBC.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Manager Mark DeRosa announced the decision on MLB Network, with Judge joining the broadcast to express his excitement: "Now, getting a chance to have 'USA' across my chest and represent all the great people in our country and represent what this country means, it's a great opportunity.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At the WBC, Judge posted a slash line of .222/.364/.481, slugging two home runs with five RBIs and six hits across seven games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Highlights included homering on his very first swing of the tournament — a 405-foot, 106.5 mph two-run blast against Brazil — and a pair of standout defensive plays from right field, throwing out runners attempting to advance to third base.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He threw out Joey Ortiz against Mexico in pool play, then did the same to Fernando Tatis Jr. against the Dominican Republic in the semi-final game with his throw clocked at 95.7 mph.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge and Team USA advanced to the championship game against Venezuela, but fell short by a score of 3–2, marking back-to-back runner-up finishes for the U.S. in the WBC.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] The offense for the U.S. went quiet in the game, with Judge going 0-for-4 with three strikeouts.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge is listed at 6 feet 7 inches (2.01 m) and 282 pounds (128 kg).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Due to his large size and strength, he has elicited comparisons to teammate Giancarlo Stanton, as well as former MLB players Richie Sexson, Dave Winfield, and Willie Stargell.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] His power output is historically significant: he is one of only eight players in MLB history to record an OPS+ above 200 in three seasons.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He is also one of just 14 players in MLB history to slug above .700 in a season with a minimum of 550 plate appearances.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He is the fourth player ever to produce four seasons with 50 or more home runs, alongside Ruth, Sammy Sosa, and Mark McGwire.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Since Statcast began tracking exit velocity in 2015, Judge broke the record for the hardest-hit home run with a 121.1 mph blast on June 10, 2017, against the Baltimore Orioles; although later surpassed, it ranked fifth as of 2025.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge and Miguel Sanó are the only MLB players since 2015 to hit multiple home runs measuring at least 495 feet.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge has been credited as a team leader both on and off the field.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He has a number of rituals before, during, and after games.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During his 2017 rookie season, Judge kept a note on his phone that read ".179", his batting average with the Yankees in 2016, and looked at it daily as a source of motivation.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge has worn the unusual uniform number of 99 since it was given to him during 2016 spring training (higher numbers are typically given to young players who are not expected to make the final regular-season roster).
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2016, Judge stated that he would have preferred either No.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] 44 (retired by the Yankees to honor Reggie Jackson) or No.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] 35 but was not sure whether he would switch if the latter two were to become available.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] MLB along with the MLB Players Association, created Players Weekend to let players "express themselves while connecting with their past in youth baseball".
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] From August 25–27, 2017, players wore alternate team jerseys inspired by youth league designs.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] They also had the option to replace their last names with their nicknames on their jersey nameplates, and the vast majority of players did so.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge chose the nickname "All Rise" (given to him by former teammate Todd Frazier) to be worn on the back of his jersey nameplate.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] For the 2018 Players Weekend, Judge chose to just have his last name on the back of his jersey.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] During the 2019 event, Judge chose his own nickname, "BAJ", an abbreviation of "Big Aaron Judge".
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge married his wife in December 2021 at a private ceremony in Maui.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] They met at Linden High School and both attended Fresno State University.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Their first child was born in January 2025.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge has two pet dachshunds named Gus and Penny.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] He grew up going to a Methodist church and has posted about his faith on his social media accounts.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge is the founder of the ALL RISE Foundation.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge's mother, Patty, serves as its executive director and president.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] At the beginning of his career, Judge had contracts with Rawlings, Under Armour, and Fanatics.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] After his 2017 rookie season, Judge signed a multi-year endorsement deal with Pepsi.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge endorsed Under Armour gear from 2014 until the 2018 season, when he signed an endorsement deal with Adidas.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In August 2023, Judge signed a shoe deal with Nike-owned Jordan Brand, becoming the fifth active MLB player to do so.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] For the 2023 season, *Legends Hospitality*, the concessions company at Yankee Stadium, announced "The 99 Burger", a California-inspired food item named after Judge's uniform number.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In March 2024, Judge was named the face of a new Ralph Lauren fragrance, "Polo Est.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] 67 Eau de Toilette" and its "Design Your Dreams" ad campaign.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In April 2024, Judge agreed to endorse energy drink Prime.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2025, Judge became the first active MLB player featured on a Big League Chew pouch when he appeared on the limited-edition "Grand Slam Grape" flavor.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge appeared on the cover of the May 15, 2017, edition of *Sports Illustrated* with the title "All Rise"*.* That same day, Judge appeared on an episode of *The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon* where he posed undercover in Bryant Park to ask Yankee fans questions about himself.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On November 6, 2017, Judge was named the cover athlete for *MLB The Show 18*.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge appeared on a 23-second skit on rapper Logic's 2022 album *Vinyl Days* named after himself.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] In 2024, Judge and his two pet dachshunds guest starred on an episode of *Rubble & Crew*, a *Paw Patrol* spin-off.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] Judge also participated in the 2026 FIFA World Cup draw on December 5, 2025.
[src:captain-baseball/aaron-judge-p01] On January 27, 2026, Judge was announced as the cover athlete for *MLB The Show 26*, becoming just the second player to appear on the game's cover twice.
[src:captain-baseball/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:captain-baseball/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:captain-baseball/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:captain-baseball/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:captain-baseball/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:captain-baseball/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:captain-baseball/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré made his MLB debut with the Dodgers in 1998 at age 19.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He led the majors with 48 home runs with the Dodgers in 2004, was the team MVP of the Red Sox in 2010, played in the 2011 World Series for the Rangers, and tied for the major league lead in hits in 2013.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 19, 2014, Beltré surpassed Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time MLB leader for hits by a Dominican player, a record since broken by Albert Pujols in 2019.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 30, 2017, Beltré became the 31st player in MLB history to reach 3,000 hits and the first Dominican player to achieve that milestone.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré retired following the 2018 season with 3,166 career hits (most by a third baseman in MLB history), 477 home runs, and 1,707 runs batted in.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He hit for the cycle three times in his career, in 2008, 2012, and 2015, one of five players to do so in MLB history, the others being Bob Meusel, Babe Herman, Trea Turner, and Christian Yelich.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won the Gold Glove Award five times, Beltré is notable for his defensive prowess and career longevity as well as his power hitting.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He played in four MLB All-Star Games and won the Silver Slugger Award four times.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Upon his retirement, Beltré was the only third baseman in history with both 3,000 career hits and 400 home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] According to Baseball Reference, Beltré has the third-highest Wins Above Replacement among third basemen.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He retired as the all-time leader amongst third basemen in hits and RBIs, and ranked third in home runs amongst third basemen.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He is also the fifth major-leaguer to have hit at least 100 home runs for three different teams.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2024, Beltré was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in his first year of eligibility.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was born on April 7, 1979, in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He attended Liceo Máximo Gómez High School.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] While working out at Campo Las Palmas in 1994, a Los Angeles Dodgers facility — one of the first of its kind for a Major League Baseball (MLB) team in the Dominican Republic — Beltré was spotted by scouts Ralph Avila and Pablo Peguero.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Though only 15 years old and weighing 130 lb (59 kg), Beltré featured a quick swing and live throwing arm.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On the insistence of Avila and Peguero, the Dodgers signed him in July 1994 with a $23,000 signing bonus.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was a highly touted prospect when he began his major league career.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] After being called up to the majors from the then-Dodgers' Double-A affiliate San Antonio Missions, Beltré made his major league debut on June 24, 1998, starting at third base in the first game of an interleague series against the Anaheim Angels.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] At the time, he was the youngest player in the National League (NL).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] During his first at-bat, Beltré hit a two-out run batted in (RBI) double off Angels starter Chuck Finley into left field to score Paul Konerko from second base to tie the game.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit his first home run six days later against Texas Rangers starter Rick Helling.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] At the end of the 1998 season, Beltré finished with 13 errors at third base while batting .215 with seven home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] At one point in the spring training prior to the start of the 1999 season, Beltré's agent, Scott Boras, commented to him that "he couldn't believe" his relatively rapid ascent to the majors and handling of "such a difficult position like third base" at age 20.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré replied that he was 19 years old, not 20.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Boras then realized that Beltré's date of birth in the Dodgers' records was incorrect and indicated the same to the team, but, that if they were to correct the mistake by compensating Beltré for signing him at younger than MLB's allowable age, they would no longer pursue the issue.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Team personnel at Las Palmas denied Boras' assertion.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] As a result, Boras and Beltré went public.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Boras convinced MLB commissioner Bud Selig to investigate the Dodgers, and MLB suspended their scouting operations in the Dominican Republic for one year, as well as Avila and Peguero.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Dodgers general manager Fred Claire, whom MLB did not contact during their investigation, publicly expressed surprise and that he was unaware of the incident.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Selig awarded Beltré $48,500 in damages.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2004, Beltré had a breakout season in which he established a number of career highs, including leading MLB with 48 home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Other career highs included batting .334, 200 hits, 121 RBI, 104 runs scored, .629 slugging percentage, and a then-career high 32 doubles.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He finished second in voting for the NL Most Valuable Player Award (MVP) and was honored with his first career Silver Slugger Award and the Babe Ruth Home Run Award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Seattle Mariners signed Beltré as a free agent before the 2005 season to a five-year, $64 million deal.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Regressing to his pre-2004 form, he batted just .255 with 19 home runs and 87 RBI.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Manager Mike Hargrove said after the season that he thought Beltré was personally disappointed in his first season in Seattle.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] After Beltré batted .167 through April 10, Ted Miller of the *Seattle Post-Intelligencer* wrote that he might become one of the Mariners' greatest busts.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He hit his first home run on April 29, raising his average to .198, and continued to improve his performance, batting .281 with 24 home runs the rest of the season.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 23, against the Boston Red Sox, Beltré hit an inside-the-park home run, the first one ever in Safeco Field history.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Though it was not a great season for Beltré, it was statistically his best as a Mariner.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He hit .276 and had 26 home runs, 99 RBI, and 41 doubles.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also won a Fielding Bible Award for being the top MLB defensive third baseman during the year.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Despite many miscues, Beltré received recognition for his defense in 2007.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He tied with Brandon Inge for the AL lead in errors by a third baseman, with 18, but ranked second in the league in assists, total chances, and range factor.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had the lowest fielding percentage of all third basemen in the league at .958.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In spite of leading third basemen in errors, Beltré won his first Gold Glove Award, becoming the first Mariners third baseman to win the award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award, as well.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 1, Beltré hit for the cycle, becoming the fourth Mariner to do so.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Arizona Diamondbacks shortstop Stephen Drew hit for the cycle that day as well, the first time two players had done so since 1920.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's decision not to wear a cup despite playing third base has been well-documented.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] This came back to hurt him on August 12, 2009, when he took a hard ground ball to the groin.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Although he stayed in for the remainder of the 14-inning victory, he was put on the 15-day disabled list (DL) after suffering bleeding in one of his testicles.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In his first game after returning from the DL, teammate Ken Griffey Jr. conspired with those responsible for the Safeco Field public address system to have Beltré's walk up music be the opening march from *The Nutcracker Suite*.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré declared free agency on November 5, 2009.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On January 7, 2010, Beltré signed a one-year, $9 million deal with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The contract had a $5 million player option for 2011 with a $1 million buyout.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] While Beltré's career before coming to the Red Sox had been regarded as somewhat disappointing, he hit .321 with 28 homers and 49 doubles in 2010, benefiting from the hitter-friendly Fenway Park.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Red Sox in batting average and tied David Ortiz for the team lead in RBIs (102).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Majors in doubles with 49 (also a career-high).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also finished fourth in the AL in batting average, and was fifth in the AL in total bases (326) and slugging percentage (.553).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also had two stolen bases on the year, and finished ninth in the MVP voting.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On January 5, 2011, Beltré signed a five-year, $80 million contract with the Texas Rangers.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He played with the Rangers for eight years until his retirement in 2018.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's statistics improved when he was in his thirties.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] While he had previously played in pitcher-friendly ballparks in Los Angeles and Seattle, the Rangers' ballpark was known as a hitter-friendly environment.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] *The Wall Street Journal* described Beltré's Rangers tenure as "nothing short of brilliant".
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was on the 2011 American League All-Star team.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 22, Beltré strained his hamstring and was also placed on the DL.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 4, he singled to right for his 2,000th career hit.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 11, Beltré hit two home runs, including the 300th of his career, against the Oakland Athletics.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was named the AL Player of the Month for September.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2011, Beltré batted .296 with 32 home runs, fifth in the AL.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was third in the American League in slugging percentage (.561), sixth in RBIs (105), and ninth in OPS (.892).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Fielding Bible said he saved 17 runs on defense in 2011.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On October 4, in Game 4 of the ALDS against the Tampa Bay Rays, Beltré became the sixth player to hit three home runs in a playoff game and the first do so in a Division Series.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in the World Series with the Rangers.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He added a fourth playoff home run in Game 5 of the World Series when he went down to one knee chasing an outside curve ball from Chris Carpenter.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Louis Cardinals defeated the Rangers in seven games.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] More recognition was bestowed on Beltré for his defense.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On November 1, he was honored with his third Gold Glove Award and first by a Ranger third baseman since Buddy Bell's six-year run from 1979 to 1984.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also won his third Fielding Bible Award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On November 2, he was awarded the Silver Slugger Award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was once again voted on to the All-Star Game starter, along with teammates Josh Hamilton and Mike Napoli.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] It was Beltré's third consecutive All-Star Game and the third of his career.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 22, against the Baltimore Orioles, Beltré hit three home runs in his first three at-bats, including two in the same inning.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He joined Pablo Sandoval, Albert Pujols, George Brett, Reggie Jackson, and Babe Ruth as the only players to hit a three-homer game in both the regular season and the postseason.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 24, he hit for the cycle for the second time in his career.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Both of his cycles came at Rangers Ballpark.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] With his first coming as a member of the Mariners, it was the first time in MLB history that a player had hit for the cycle more than once at the same stadium.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He joined Joe DiMaggio as the only players in big league history to have a three-homer game and a cycle in the same week.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] For his efforts, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for August 20–26.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] During the week, he hit .433 (13-for-30) with three doubles, one triple, five home runs, nine RBI, and seven runs scored.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had the highest slugging percentage (1.100) in the majors, the most total bases (33), was tied for first in hits and home runs, and tied for second in RBI.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] After the season, Beltré won more defensive accolades.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award and fourth overall.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was won a Gold Glove Award and his second Platinum Glove Award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Wilson Sporting Goods honored him as one of their Defensive Players of the Year in the first year of that award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Rangers organization named Beltré the team captain in 2013.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for July 1–7.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He batted .478 (11-for-23) with four home runs, two doubles and five RBI in six games.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He led the American League in home runs, slugging (1.087), OPS (1.607), total bases (25), and extra-base hits (six) while producing the fourth-highest batting average.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit safely in all six games with two or more hits four times.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had the 24th multi-homer game of his career with a pair of home runs on July 4 against Seattle.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Maintaining his strong hitting throughout July, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Month, his fourth career monthly award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He batted .369 with four doubles, nine homers, 19 RBI, and 13 runs scored over 26 games.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He tied for the major league monthly lead in home runs with Alfonso Soriano and total bases with Torii Hunter (69).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré also was among the AL leaders in slugging percentage (second, .670), hits (tied for second, 38), extra-base hits (tied for fourth, 13), RBI (tied for fifth) and batting average (sixth).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He capped off the month with a walk-off home run to lead the Rangers past the Angels on July 31, the seventh walk-off home run of his career and first with Texas.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] It was his third monthly award with Texas, making him one of seven players to win multiple times with the Rangers, including Josh Hamilton (four), Rafael Palmeiro, Alex Rodriguez (both with three), Iván Rodríguez, Juan González and Rubén Sierra (two each).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] For the season, Beltré played in 161 games and totaled a .315 average, 30 homers, 92 RBI and .509 slugging percentage.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He led the AL with 199 hits and was fourth in batting average and fifth in total bases (321).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also made the top-10 in games played, slugging percentage and home runs.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In the AL MVP voting, he was tied for seventh place.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Dallas-Fort Worth chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association of America named Beltré the Texas Rangers Player of the Year.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On May 7, while facing Jorge de la Rosa of the Colorado Rockies, Beltré hit his 100th home run as a member of the Rangers, becoming the fifth player in major league history to hit 100 home runs with three teams, following Darrell Evans, Reggie Jackson, Alex Rodriguez, and Jim Thome.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On June 24, Beltré singled off Drew Smyly of the Detroit Tigers for his 2,500th career hit and the first hit of a 4-for-4 game.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On September 18, Beltré singled off Sonny Gray in the first inning for his 2,591st hit, surpassing Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time hit leader among Dominican-born players.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré finished the 2014 season batting .324, his highest average since 2004, with 19 home runs and 77 RBI in 148 games.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In February, the Rangers picked up Beltré's option, which would have become guaranteed if he had reached 586 plate appearances in the 2015 season.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] While playing against Cleveland on May 15, Beltré hit his 400th home run on a sinker from Bruce Chen.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He became the 52nd player in MLB history to reach that plateau, and the fourth to do so while playing at least 75 percent of his games at third base.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 3, Beltré hit for the cycle with hits in each of the first, second, third, and fifth innings at home against the Houston Astros in a 12–9 win.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] It was his third career cycle, second as a Ranger, and third at the Rangers' home park, making him the only player ever to hit three cycles in one stadium.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He became the first Rangers player to hit for multiple cycles.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The first player in 82 years to hit for a third cycle, he became the fourth player to do so and tied the major league record for total career cycles, joining Long John Reilly, Bob Meusel, and Babe Herman.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] During the last week of the season, and the Rangers' run towards the AL West championship, Beltré batted .448 with two home runs and 13 RBI.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also went 2-for-4 with a home in the final game of the season to help the Rangers advance to their sixth AL West title.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He finished the season with 18 home runs, 83 RBI, 163 hits, and .287 average.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Enduring a torn ligament in his left thumb over the last three months of the season, Beltré had surgery to repair it immediately after the season ended.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The Phi Delta Theta fraternity presented Beltré with the 2014 Lou Gehrig Memorial Award on September 17, 2015, making him the first Rangers player to win the award.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On April 15, Beltré and the Rangers agreed to a two-year, $36 million contract extension that would last through the 2018 seasons.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] The extension prevented Beltré from becoming a free agent at the end of the season.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Displaying a drop to one knee, Beltré hit a home run on a curve ball from Jesse Hahn of Oakland on May 17.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In a May 29 game against the Pittsburgh Pirates, Beltré hit a two-run home run off Juan Nicasio to give him 1,501 career RBI, making him the 54th player to reach the milestone and the fourth third baseman.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 2, Beltré became the 28th player all time to amass 10,000 career at-bats.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 23, he became the 36th player all time to record 11,000 career plate appearances.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Two days later, he hit a walk-off home run, the ninth of his career, against the Athletics in the bottom of the ninth inning for a 7−6 win.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On August 24, Beltré, in a game against the Cincinnati Reds, hit a go-ahead two-out double for his 2,900th career hit and led the Rangers to a 6–5 win.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] With this hit, Beltré became the 39th player in major league history to reach the milestone.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré would once again show his signature home run knee drop after hitting a solo shot in the second inning in a game against the Houston Astros on September 13.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] His 30th of the season, it was the first time he reached the mark since 2013 and fifth in his career.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Ten days later, his two-run home run in the eighth inning against the Athletics aided the Rangers in clinching the AL West division crown for the second year in a row and the seventh in franchise history.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also reached 100 RBI for the first time since 2012 and fifth time in his career.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He won the Gold Glove at third base, the fifth of his career.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré began the 2017 season on the 10-day disabled list after injuring his right leg near the end of spring training.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 4, Beltré hit his 600th career double, becoming the 17th player all-time to reach that milestone.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 7, Beltré became the 21st player to amass 5,000 career total bases.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On July 26, Beltré was ejected by umpire Gerry Davis; in a game against the Miami Marlins, Davis asked Beltré, who was the next scheduled batter, to move closer to the on-deck circle.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré responded by picking up the edge of the logo that marked the on-deck circle and moving it closer to where he had been standing, which prompted Davis to eject him.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré collected his 3,000th hit with a double into left field against Wade Miley of the Baltimore Orioles on July 30, making him the 31st player to reach this milestone and the first Dominican-born player to accomplish it.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in only 94 games in 2017 due to hamstring and calf problems.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Prior to the start of the 2018 season, the Rangers signed Bartolo Colón, giving them the only two active players with at least 20 seasons in the major leagues and the last two active players to have played in 1990s.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On April 5, Beltré doubled in the second inning versus the Oakland Athletics to pass Rod Carew as the all-time Latin American hits leader.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On June 13, Beltré hit a double that gave him 3,090 career hits; this made him the all-time leader in hits by a player not born in the United States, surpassing former Mariners teammate Ichiro Suzuki.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On November 20, 2018, Beltré announced his retirement.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2,933 games over 21 seasons, Beltré posted a .286 batting average with 3,166 hits, 477 home runs, 1,707 RBI, 121 stolen bases, 1,524 runs, 636 doubles, a .339 on-base percentage, a .480 slugging percentage, and a .960 fielding percentage.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 28 postseason games, he hit .261 with five home runs and 11 RBI.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré is regarded as one of the greatest third basemen of all time.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won five Gold Gloves, he was notable for his longevity, fielding ability, and power hitting.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's signature home run swing included a drop to one knee when connecting with a breaking ball, particularly notable during Game 5 of the 2011 World Series against Cardinals ace Chris Carpenter.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré's defensive style was somewhat unorthodox.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Rangers manager Ron Washington remarked that Beltré fielded ground balls incorrectly by stopping before catching the ball and relying very little on the positioning of his feet in throwing the ball to first base.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré explained that his arm was so strong that early in his career he was making many throwing errors; by planting his feet, he was able to improve his accuracy despite his lack of proper foot positioning.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Another major league manager, Joe Maddon, compared the unique style of Beltré's defensive play to Ozzie Smith's "flair at shortstop", Stan Musial's "coiled batting stance", and the way Steve Carlton wrapped his left wrist before releasing a slider.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Commented Maddon further on Beltré's defense, "There's a lot of guys that did things unique to them that weren't out of the *Spalding Guide*.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He's a super smart player, knows where to position himself." Beltré was known for the sense of playfulness and joy that he exhibited on the field.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He had a routine with Rangers shortstop Elvis Andrus on pop flies where both men put their arms up to catch the ball.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] During a game against the Red Sox on June 26, 2016, Sandy León hit a foul ball which landed in the first row in the stands, just out of Beltré's reach.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] However, instead of returning immediately to the infield, he reached very close to the ball in a motion, pretending as if he were going to take it away from the fan who caught León's foul ball.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] As a hitter, Beltré also regularly pointed to the first base umpire to appeal a checked swing, a move usually only done by catchers.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré also had a joking relationship with Mariners pitcher Felix Hernández, which included Beltré getting ejected in 2010, when the two former teammates first faced each other, and Hernández hugging Beltré on the field in 2017, the day after Beltré's 3,000th major league hit.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was also known for his dislike of anyone touching the top of his head.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Before the game where he recorded his 3,000th hit, he let his teammates touch his head.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Much to his dismay, the act turned into a game, inducing repeat offenders, including Andrus.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] After a game in which he hit a grand slam that provided the decisive runs in a 5–2 win over the Athletics on August 15, 2016, he took a broom from the groundskeepers closet and began combing an area of infield dirt.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Still, Rougned Odor trotted to Beltré carrying a full drink bucket but missed drenching Beltré when he threw the blue sports drink at his teammate.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré played for the Dominican Republic in the 2006 World Baseball Classic (WBC).
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He was named to the All-WBC team after hitting 4 home runs in six games.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He also played in the 2017 WBC, batting 1-for-15 in four games.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2017, he was dealing with leg injuries that caused him to miss the beginning of the MLB season.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré was one of several Dominican Hall of Famers assisting general manager Nelson Cruz ahead of the 2026 WBC.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] On June 5, 2023, Beltré was named the honorary general manager for the Karachi Monarchs of the Baseball United league for their inaugural season.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré served as the manager for the American League team in the 2024 All-Star Futures Game.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré has contributed to humanitarian activities in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex such as the Texas Rangers Baseball Foundation, Texas Rangers RBI program, the I Love Baseball program, which operates in the Dominican Republic, and the Baseball Tomorrow Fund.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] He has donated to Dave Valle's Esperanza International as well as foundations established by other major-league players, including Robinson Chirinos, Eddie Guardado, Joakim Soria, and Michael Young.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] In 2021, Beltré helped pay to reconstruct a baseball stadium in the Dominican Republic where he grew up playing.
[src:captain-baseball/adrián-beltré] Beltré and his wife have three children.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Quick retrieval of loose balls and delivery of the game balls to the servers are necessary for quick play in tennis.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In professional tournaments, every court will have a trained squad of ball boys/girls with positionings and movements designed for maximum efficiency, while also not interfering with active play.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] As well as dealing with the game balls, ball boys/girls may also provide the players with other assistance, such as the delivery of towels and drinks.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] There are various methods for selecting the ball boys and girls for a tournament.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In many tournaments, such as Wimbledon and the Queen's Club Championships, they are picked from or apply through schools, where they are selected by tournaments, and they have to go through a number of selections and tests.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In some other tournaments, such as the Nottingham Open, Australian Open and the US Open, positions are advertised and there are open try-outs.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Applicants are required to pass a physical ability assessment.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In addition to fitness and stamina, the abilities to concentrate and remain alert are essential.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In 2006, the IFAB Laws of the Game of association football were changed to allow multiple balls to be used under the direction of a referee.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Higher level organised matches now commonly use 6+ balls with ball boys scattered around the pitch to quicken the pace of play.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Typically positioned behind advertising boards surrounding the pitch, ball boys will try to be in possession of a spare ball at all times, so that this can be given to the players prior to the loose ball being retrieved.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Balls may also be stored on cones near sidelines, so that they are readily available for restarts, and to prevent ball boys from accelerating returns to home players, and delaying returns to away players.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Methods for selecting ball boys vary between grounds.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] On occasion, away teams have complained about perceived favour of ball boys towards home sides.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In a 2013 EFL Cup match Eden Hazard, a member of the away team, which was trailing at the time, got into an altercation with an apparently time-wasting ball boy who was lying on top of the ball.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Hazard was subsequently sent off for violent conduct and suspended for three games.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Ball kids are stationed in out-of-play areas near the first and third base foul lines to retrieve out-of-play baseballs.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] They should not be confused with bat boys and bat girls, who remain in or near a team's dugout and the home plate area, primarily to tend to a team's baseball bats.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] As ball kids are stationed on the field, albeit in foul territory, they can occasionally interfere with play; such events are governed by Rule 6.01(d), the main point of which is that if the interference is unintentional, any live ball remains alive and in play.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] For this reason, most teams will use experienced individuals who understand the rules, to minimize mistaken interference.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] One of the more infamous examples was the use of a Hooters girl as a promotion.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] The woman unfortunately snagged a ball that was fair and live in a Tampa Bay Rays game, throwing it to the fans.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] The batter was awarded a double on the interference.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Since 1992, the San Francisco Giants have employed older men as "balldudes", instead of the traditional youths.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In 1993, Corinne Mullane became the first "balldudette", and she and her daughter Molly, who began working as a balldudette in the 2000s, have since been included in the National Baseball Hall of Fame as the first mother-daughter ball-retrieving duo in baseball.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] Ball boys are stationed around the field just outside the boundary to retrieve any balls struck into the spectator stands or to the boundary rope.
[src:captain-baseball/ball-boy] In India, disabled people are not allowed to be ball-boys anymore after a controversy occurred in 2017, after criticism of the Board of Control for Cricket in India surrounding the appearance of a polio-afflicted fan who had been serving as a ball-boy for a few years.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He briefly played in the minor leagues before making his MLB debut in 1986.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He quickly won the starting shortstop role for the Reds and enjoyed a long run of strong seasons with the team.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin struggled with a string of injuries between 1997 and 2003, limiting his playing time in several seasons.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin retired after the 2004 season and worked in a front-office position for the Washington Nationals for several years until he joined ESPN as a baseball analyst.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He served as a coach for the American team in the 2009 World Baseball Classic and managed the Brazilian national team for the same event in 2013.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin is considered one of the top players of his era, winning nine Silver Slugger awards, three Gold Glove awards, and the 1995 National League Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He was selected to the Major League All-Star Game twelve times, and was one of the pivotal players on the 1990 Reds' World Series championship team.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2012, Larkin was elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Born and raised in the Cincinnati suburb of Silverton, Ohio, and raised Catholic, Larkin attended Archbishop Moeller High School.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin accepted a football scholarship to the University of Michigan to play for coach Bo Schembechler, but during his freshman year, he decided to play baseball exclusively.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He was a two-time All-American and led the Wolverines to berths in two College World Series, in 1983 and 1984, the program's last until 2019.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin was also named Big Ten Player of the Year in 1984 and 1985.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin's number 16 was retired by the school on May 1, 2010.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin played for the United States national team at the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Barry Larkin played with the Vermont Reds on their team that won the 1985 Eastern League Championship and in 1986 was the Rookie of the Year and Triple-A Player of the Year with the Denver Zephyrs.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In all, he played only 177 minor league games in his professional career.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] After arriving in the majors, Larkin battled fellow prospect Kurt Stillwell for the starting shortstop spot before establishing himself as the starter in 1987.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 1988, Larkin led all major leaguers by striking out only 24 times in 588 at-bats.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin batted .353 in the 1990 World Series to help lead the Reds to a four-game sweep of the Oakland Athletics.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] On June 27–28, 1991, Larkin became the first shortstop ever to hit five home runs over two consecutive games.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He earned his fourth consecutive All-Star Game selection that season.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] After the 1991 season, Larkin questioned the Reds' commitment to winning.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He said he was likely to leave the team when his contract expired the next year, but he was encouraged when the Reds acquired pitchers Tim Belcher and Greg Swindell in the offseason.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In January 1992, the Reds signed him to a five-year, $25.6 million contract.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] At that time, only four players had larger contracts and Larkin was the highest-paid shortstop.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin was not selected as an All-Star in 1992, but he won his fifth consecutive Silver Slugger Award.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 1993, he won the Roberto Clemente Award, which recognizes players who display sportsmanship, community service and on-field ability.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 1995, Larkin finished sixth in batting (.319) and second in stolen bases (51) to win the National League's MVP award, the first by a shortstop since Maury Wills in 1962.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He led the Reds to the National League Central division title and the National League Championship Series, where he batted .389 during the series loss to the eventual champion Atlanta Braves.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 1996, Larkin hit a career-high 33 home runs and stole 36 bases, becoming the first shortstop in Major League history to join the 30–30 club.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He arguably had a better season in 1996 than he had in his MVP year of 1995, as his on-base percentage and slugging percentage were both improved.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin was named the Reds' captain before the 1997 season, making him the first player to hold the honor since Dave Concepción's retirement.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Beginning that season, Larkin suffered a series of injuries throughout the last few years of his career.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He missed 55 games that year due to injuries to his calf and Achilles tendon.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] About three weeks before the opening of the 1998 season, Larkin decided to undergo neck surgery for a perforated disk.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He was not in severe pain, but he was unable to lift his arm enough to play defense.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] On September 27, 1998, Barry, his brother Stephen Larkin, second baseman Bret Boone, and third baseman Aaron Boone all played the infield at the same time for the last game of the 1998 season, making it the first time in MLB history that an infield was composed entirely of two pairs of brothers.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 1999, Larkin was nearly traded to the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He later said that he was approached by a Los Angeles clubhouse attendant, who gave him a Dodgers jersey with his name on it.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] The jersey had been prepared as trade negotiations advanced so that the teams could be prepared for a press conference about the trade.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Also in 1999, Larkin served as a pre-game analyst for NBC's coverage of the World Series alongside host Hannah Storm.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In July 2000, Larkin blocked a trade to the New York Mets to remain with the Reds.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] The trade would have sent three players, top minor league outfielder Alex Escobar, pitcher Eric Cammack and pitcher Jason Saenz, from the Mets to the Reds in exchange for Larkin.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin said that he would have gone to New York, as he enjoyed playing there, but the Mets did not want to sign him to a multi-year contract.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] The Reds signed him to a three-year contract extension worth $27 million.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In the 2000 season, Larkin missed 59 games after he injured his finger twice and he suffered a knee sprain.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He underwent finger surgery in April and knee surgery in September.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin struggled with a groin injury in 2001, prompting criticism of his play.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Broadcaster Joe Nuxhall said on air that Larkin had "lost it".
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] By August, the injury had limited Larkin to 45 games.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He underwent season-ending surgery for a hernia that had been diagnosed during an evaluation of the groin injury.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] During the 2002 season, Larkin played in 145 games but hit for the lowest batting average (.245) since his first full year in the major leagues.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Though he did not miss many games, Larkin dealt with injuries to his rib cage, hamstring, shoulder, neck and toe.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2003, Larkin had spent two stints on the disabled list with calf injuries by late May.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] During strained contract negotiations with Reds chief operating officer John Allen in late 2003, Larkin almost left the team.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin and the Reds agreed to a one-year contract for 2004.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin called off a planned retirement ceremony scheduled for October 2, 2004, because he was not sure if he would retire.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In that season, Larkin hit for a .289 batting average in his final season.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He announced his retirement in February 2005.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Commenting on Larkin's retirement after such a strong season, sports columnist Terence Moore drew a comparison to the retirement of Ted Williams.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He wrote, "Barry Larkin wasn't quite Williams at the end, but he was in the vicinity when it comes to the big picture...
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Baseball writer Bill James has called Larkin one of the greatest shortstops of all time, ranking him #6 all time in his *New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He became the first major league shortstop to join the 30–30 club when he had 33 home runs and 36 stolen bases in 1996.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] After his retirement, Larkin was hired as a special assistant to the general manager in the Washington Nationals organization.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] With the Nationals, he worked under former Reds general manager Jim Bowden.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin had hoped to work for the Reds, but *USA Today* reported that his 2003 contract disagreement with Allen eliminated that opportunity.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2008, he signed with the MLB Network as a studio analyst.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He was the bench coach for the United States at the 2009 World Baseball Classic and managed the United States' second-round game against Puerto Rico when U.S. manager Davey Johnson left to attend his stepson's wedding.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] On July 20, 2008, he was inducted into the Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame and Museum.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2009, he was inducted into the National College Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2011, Larkin left Washington for ESPN to serve as a *Baseball Tonight* analyst.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2012, Larkin was voted into the Hall of Fame with 86.4% of the vote.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He was the eighth Reds player and 24th shortstop inducted to the Hall of Fame.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] On August 25, 2012, his number 11 was retired in an official ceremony at Great American Ball Park.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2010, his first year of eligibility for the Hall of Fame, Larkin had received 51.6% of the vote (75 percent is needed for election).
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In 2011, he received 62.1% of the vote, the highest of non-inducted players and third overall.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He was invited by the Brazilian Baseball Federation to manage their national team in the qualifiers for the 2013 World Baseball Classic.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Brazil beat host country Panama in Brazil's first time to qualify for the event.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin said Brazil was originally scheduled to play in Puerto Rico, but because of the huge Japanese baseball influence in Brazil, they played in Japan.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] The team played Cuba and China besides the home country.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] The team went winless in its WBC debut and was eliminated after the first round.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In November 2013, Detroit Tigers general manager Dave Dombrowski confirmed that the organization had intended to interview Larkin for its open managerial position.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin declined the interview due to the time commitment associated with the job.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Brad Ausmus was named the new Tigers manager on November 3, 2013.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In November 2014, the *Tampa Bay Times* reported that Larkin was among 10 candidates interviewed for the Tampa Bay Rays' managerial job.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin was not among the team's three finalists, and the job ultimately went to Kevin Cash.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin joined the Cincinnati Reds as a minor-league roving infield instructor in May 2015.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He helped out the big-league club during spring training 2016.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] When asked whether he hoped to manage in the future, he said, "Never say never.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] The conditions have to be right and, you know, the manager's job, at least in my opinion, is not about just having the manager's position.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In September 2016, Larkin managed Brazil at the 2017 World Baseball Classic qualification, where the team failed to qualify for the final tournament after losing to Great Britain.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] On February 16, 2021, it was announced that Larkin joined the Reds' television broadcast team on Fox Sports Ohio.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] On January 29, 2025, it was announced that Larkin would join the effort to bring Major League Baseball to Orlando, Florida as the MLB Ambassador for the Orlando Dreamers.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin has also been an active participant in the SportsUnited Sports Envoy program for the U.S.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In this function, he has traveled to Colombia, Ecuador, India, Lithuania, Taiwan, where he worked with to conduct baseball clinics and events that reached more than 2,200 youth from underserved areas.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] In so doing, Larkin helped contribute to SportsUnited's mission to reach out to youth populations in order to promote growth and a stable democratic government.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin's brother, Stephen Larkin, was also a professional baseball player; he made it to the major leagues for one game with the Reds in 1998.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Another brother, Byron Larkin, was a second-team All-American basketball player at Xavier University and is the color commentator on Xavier basketball radio broadcasts.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin's eldest brother, Mike, was a captain of the Notre Dame football team in 1985.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Larkin and his wife have two daughters and a son, Shane.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] Shane played two seasons at the University of Miami before being a first round draft pick in the 2013 NBA draft.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] He played for four NBA teams in 4 seasons, starting 41 times.
[src:captain-baseball/barry-larkin] His oldest daughter, Brielle D'Shea, is named in honor of Shea Stadium, as Larkin enjoyed playing there.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] In baseball, **base running** is the act of running from base to base, performed by members of the team at bat.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Base running is a tactical part of the game with the goal of eventually reaching home base (home plate) to score a run.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Batters strive to become base runners, and to enable existing base runners to move to a subsequent base or to score.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] In statistics, the number of baserunners (for example those allowed by a pitcher) is denoted by the abbreviation **BR**.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] The Official Baseball Rules uses the term **batter-runner** to identify the batter from the time he becomes a base runner until the end of the same play, whether he is successful at legally attaining first base or any subsequent base.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] The term is not applied if the batter is awarded first base (the last three items in the above list).
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] If a base runner's teammate is put out for the third out of the inning, the base runner is said to be left on base (LOB).
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] A runner who is touching a base which he is entitled to occupy may not be tagged out.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Runners may attempt to advance from base to base on any fair ball that touches the ground.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] When a ball is hit in the air (i.e., a *fly ball*) and caught by the defending team, runners must return and touch the base they occupy—called *tagging up*—after the ball is first touched by a fielder.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Once they do this, they may attempt to advance at their own risk.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] On a ball that touches the ground in fair territory, if there is a force, runners are required to run.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Base runners may attempt to advance at any time while the ball is alive, even before or while the pitcher is throwing a pitch.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] The catcher—or pitcher, in lieu of delivering the pitch—often tries to prevent this by throwing the ball to one of the infielders in order to tag the runner.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] This *pick-off attempt* is usually unsuccessful in tagging out the runner but is effective in keeping the runner closer to the base.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] If the runner is tagged out while diving back to the base, it is called a *pickoff*.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] If the runner attempts to advance to the next base but is tagged out before reaching it safely, he is *caught stealing*.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] A successful attempt by the runner is called a *stolen base*.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] If a pitch gets away from the catcher, runners may also try to advance.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] This may be a *wild pitch*, if the pitcher is held responsible for the ball getting away, or a *passed ball* if the catcher is deemed to be at fault.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Sometimes the defending team will ignore a runner who is trying to steal a base; in this case a runner is not credited with a steal, and the base is attributed to *defensive indifference*.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] An infielder who cleanly fields a ball hit on the ground, then throws it quickly and accurately, will usually get the ball to a base before the runner runs the 90 feet (27 m).
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] However, any hesitation or mistake on the part of the fielder may allow the runner to reach the base safely.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Teams scout the opposition and take advantage of players who are poor at defense.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] For example, on a deep fly ball to center field with a man on second base, if the center fielder has a weak arm, the runner on second base may tag the base and attempt to reach third despite the risks of being tagged out.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Base running and hitting are coordinated to produce better results in the squeeze play and the hit and run play.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] When the count is full and there are two outs, any runners forced to advance begin running as soon as the pitcher's motion obliges him to complete his pitch, as their distance from the base will not be the cause of any third out.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Good runners also try to get extra bases when a play is being made at a different base.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] For example, a batter who hits a single should determine whether the defense's focus on another runner gives the batter a chance to reach second base.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Sliding into a base is an important part of base running.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] The pop-up slide both ensures that the runner touches the base and elevates him to an upright posture to help him take additional bases if the defense misperforms.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] A take-out slide tries to use a collision with a fielder to keep him from taking additional action, such as throwing to achieve a double play.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] However, this move, when made independently of the attempt to reach the base, has been illegal since 2016 because of the potential for injury.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] The base coach at third base, and any batter still at home plate, may watch the ball approaching the base and may signal the base runner on the optimum slide to avoid being tagged out.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] The most baserunners allowed by a pitcher in a game since 1901 is 39, by Eddie Rommel, who pitched 17 innings in relief for the Philadelphia Athletics to defeat the Cleveland Indians, 18–17, on July 10, 1932.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] The record number of baserunners in a season is 820, by John Coleman of the Philadelphia Quakers in 1883.
[src:captain-baseball/base-running] Wilbur Wood of the 1973 Chicago White Sox was the last pitcher to allow more than 500 baserunners in a season.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] In baseball, a captain is an honorary title sometimes given to a member of the team to acknowledge his leadership.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Few Major League teams today have captains.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] In the early days of baseball, a captain was a player who was responsible for many of the functions now assumed by managers and coaches, such as preparing lineups, making decisions about strategy, and encouraging teamwork.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] In amateur or youth baseball, a manager or coach may appoint a team captain to assist in communicating with the players and to encourage teamwork and improvement.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] The official rules of Major League Baseball (MLB) only briefly mention the position of team captain.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Official Baseball Rule 4.03 Comment (formerly Rule 4.01 Comment), which discusses the submission of a team's lineup card to the umpire, notes that obvious errors in the lineup should be brought to the attention of the team's manager or captain.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Only a few major league teams have had captains in recent years, two examples being Adrián Beltré of the Texas Rangers and David Wright of the New York Mets, both of whom served in the role from 2013 through 2018.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] As of the 2023 season, the New York Yankees and Kansas City Royals are the only teams with captains; Aaron Judge was named the Yankees' captain on December 21, 2022 and Salvador Pérez was named the Royals' captain on March 30, 2023.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Jerry Remy, who was named as captain of the California Angels in 1977 at age 24, explains that in today's modern age of baseball, "there's probably no need for a captain on a major league team.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] I think there are guys who lead by example.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Baseball captains in MLB generally do not wear an NHL-style "C" on their jersey.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Mike Sweeney, captain of the Kansas City Royals from 2003 to 2007, wore the "C" patch, as did John Franco and Keith Hernandez of the Mets, Barry Larkin of the Cincinnati Reds and Jason Varitek of the Boston Red Sox.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Brandon Belt of the San Francisco Giants wore an unofficial "C" patch (made from electrical tape) in a game on September 10, 2021, as a joke.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Of the current captains in MLB, only Salvador Pérez wears the "C" patch.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] In the 19th and early 20th century, the captain held most of the on-field responsibilities that are held by managers and coaches in modern baseball.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] In contrast with modern baseball, the 1898 rules did not mention the managers having any rights to interact with the umpires.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] The rules allowed managers to sit on the team's bench during the game, but were otherwise silent with respect to rights and responsibilities of managers.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] In early baseball, many teams had playing managers who had both the off-field responsibilities of managers and the on-field responsibilities of captains.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] They held the title of "manager-captain." In contrast, teams that had non-playing managers hired a player to serve as captain.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] For example, in early 1902, Jack Doyle was signed as captain and first baseman of the New York Giants while non-player Horace Fogel was manager.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] The role of captain has been significant in the histories of some teams, such as the Yankees, Red Sox, and Giants.
[src:captain-baseball/captain-baseball] Conversely, some teams have never named a captain, such as the Milwaukee Brewers.
